"Augustin J., Merbach W., Schmidt W., Reining E.","Effect of changing temperature and water table on trace gas emission from minerotrophic mires",1996,"Journal of Applied Botany","70","1-2",,"45","51",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0029787044&partnerID=40&md5=882e7d2f2415d6172e75c3718ee08393","Inst. F. Rhizospharenforschung P., Zentrum F. Agrarlandschafts- L.; Inst. F. Bodenlandschaftsforschung, Zentrum F. Agrarlandschafts- L.; Inst. F. Landnutzungs-Syst. L., Zentrum F. Agrarlandschafts- L.; Zentrum F. Agrarlandschafts- L., Inst. F. Rhizospharenforschung P., Eberswalder Straße 84, D-15374 Müncheberg, Germany","Augustin, J., Inst. F. Rhizospharenforschung P., Zentrum F. Agrarlandschafts- L., Zentrum F. Agrarlandschafts- L., Inst. F. Rhizospharenforschung P., Eberswalder Straße 84, D-15374 Müncheberg, Germany; Merbach, W., Inst. F. Rhizospharenforschung P., Zentrum F. Agrarlandschafts- L., Zentrum F. Agrarlandschafts- L., Inst. F. Rhizospharenforschung P., Eberswalder Straße 84, D-15374 Müncheberg, Germany; Schmidt, W., Inst. F. Bodenlandschaftsforschung, Zentrum F. Agrarlandschafts- L., Zentrum F. Agrarlandschafts- L., Inst. F. Rhizospharenforschung P., Eberswalder Straße 84, D-15374 Müncheberg, Germany; Reining, E., Inst. F. Landnutzungs-Syst. L., Zentrum F. Agrarlandschafts- L., Zentrum F. Agrarlandschafts- L., Inst. F. Rhizospharenforschung P., Eberswalder Straße 84, D-15374 Müncheberg, Germany","Peatlands, hydromorphous soils with high organic matter content, display, as a result of anaerobic conditions, a delayed litter decomposition and therefore constitute important terrestric sinks for carbon and nitrogen compounds. In spite of their relatively small area proportion of approx. 3% (3.88 - 4.38 × 106 km2), peatlands contain approx. 30% of the world's soil carbon and nitrogen reserves. Several signs indicate that substantial drainage and increasing temperatures due to the increasing cultivation of peatlands and the global climate change could result in a large-scale conversion of peatlands from C/N sinks to C/N sources. Irrespective of many uncertain details and complex interactions with other factors, the lowering of the groundwater table of peatlands actually seems to strongly enhance the net release of the radiatively active trace gases carbon dioxide and nitrous oxide, reducing at the same time the high emissions of methane that occur in natural peatlands. The antizipated climate change will probably induce large-scale shifts in the distribution of the different peatland ecosystems along with considerable changes of the trace gas emissions. In view of this development, a net loss of global peatland area along with an increase in their contribution to the greenhouse effect must be expected.",,,,,,,,"Augustin, J., Merbach, W., Käding, H., Schmidt, W., Schalitz, G., Lachgas- und Methanemissionen aus degradierten Niedermoor-standorten Nordostdeutschlands unter dem Einfluß unterschiedlicher Bewirtschaftung (1996) Geotechnica-Fachbuch (im Druck), , Ernst u. Sohn Verlag, Berlin; Bartlett, K., Harriss, R., Review and assessment of methane emissions from wetlands (1993) Chemosphere, 26, pp. 261-320; Bridgeham, S.D., Richardson, C.J., Mechanisms controlling soil respiration (CO, and N,O) in southern peatlands (1992) Soil Biol. Biochem., 24, pp. 1089-1099; Bridgeham, S.D., Johnston, C.A., Pastor, J., Updegraff, K., Potential feedbacks of northern wetlands on climate change (1995) Bio-Science, 45, pp. 262-274; Cannell, M.G.R., Devar, R.C., Pyatt, D.G., Conifer plantations on drained peatlands in Britain: A net gain or loss of carbon? (1993) Forestry, 66, pp. 354-369; Dunfield, P., Knowles, R., Dumont, R., Moore, T.R., Methane production and consumption in temperate and subarctic peat soils: Response to temperature and pH (1993) Soil Biol. Biochem., 25, pp. 321-326; Duxbury, J.M., Bouldin, D.R., Terry, R.E., Tate, R.L., Emissions of nitrous oxide from soils (1983) Nature, 298, pp. 462-464; Duxbury, J.M., Har